---
import BaseLayout from "../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
import { projectMetadata } from "../config/project";
import { withBase } from "../domain/base-path";

const methodologyPath = withBase("/methodology");
const licensePath = withBase("/legal/license");
---

<BaseLayout
  title="About"
  description="About GraphRoots, an independent public project for exploring the people, traditions, recordings, places, and pathways through which music travels."
  canonicalPath="/about"
>
  <article class="shell about-page reading">
    <p class="eyebrow">{projectMetadata.attribution}</p>

    <h1>About GraphRoots</h1>

    <p class="lede">
      GraphRoots is an independent public research and visualization project
      exploring how music travels through artists, traditions, recordings,
      places, scenes, institutions, technologies, and historical events.
    </p>

    <h2>Music as a network</h2>

    <p>
      Musical history does not unfold through a single line of descent.
      Traditions are transmitted through mentorship, migration, performance,
      collaboration, recorded sound, adaptation, revival, and shared cultural
      settings. These relationships overlap, diverge, and sometimes remain
      uncertain or disputed.
    </p>

    <p>
      GraphRoots uses interactive graphs to make these pathways explorable
      without reducing every connection to a generic claim of influence.
      Relationship types, supporting evidence, editorial status, and
      disagreement remain visible wherever the available sources allow.
    </p>

    <h2>Why begin with the blues?</h2>

    <p>
      The blues offers a powerful starting point because its history connects
      African musical traditions, African American life in the American South,
      migration, recording industries, regional scenes, technological change,
      transatlantic revival, and worldwide reinterpretation.
    </p>

    <p>
      <strong>GraphRoots / Blues: Roots &amp; Branches</strong> is the first collection
      developed on the platform. It traces selected connections among artists, ensembles,
      traditions, recordings, places, scenes, and revivals. It is an early, curated
      release and an evolving research corpus, not a complete genealogy or a final
      account of blues history.
    </p>

    <h2>A curated and evolving corpus</h2>

    <p>
      Every reviewed public relationship represents a specific historical claim.
      Records are classified, sourced, reviewed, and versioned independently.
      The absence of a connection does not mean that no historical relationship
      existed; it means only that the current release does not yet contain a
      sufficiently defined and supported record.
    </p>

    <p>
      The project also acknowledges that surviving archives are uneven.
      Commercial success, access to recording and distribution, segregation,
      institutional collecting, and later canon formation all influence which
      musicians and traditions are easiest to document.
    </p>

    <p>
      The principles used to define relationships, assign direction, evaluate
      evidence, represent disagreement, and prepare public releases are
      described on the <a href={methodologyPath}>Methodology page</a>.
    </p>

    <h2>Open project</h2>

    <p>
      The GraphRoots website and corpus are developed openly. The <a
        href={projectMetadata.repositoryUrl}
        >source code, structured data, release history, and documentation</a
      > are maintained together so that the project can be examined, cited, reused,
      and improved.
    </p>

    <p>
      The software and associated documentation are available under the <a
        href={licensePath}>MIT License</a
      >. Third-party media and source materials remain subject to their own
      rights and terms.
    </p>

    <h2>Corrections and contributions</h2>

    <p>
      GraphRoots welcomes well-sourced corrections, clarifications, and
      proposals for missing relationships. Submissions should identify the
      relevant record, describe the proposed change, and provide sources that
      can be independently reviewed.
    </p>

    <p>
      <a href={projectMetadata.correctionsUrl}>Open a corpus correction issue</a
      >
      in the project repository. Accepted changes are recorded in the corpus changelog
      and included in a subsequent versioned release.
    </p>

    <h2>Independence</h2>

    <p>
      GraphRoots is currently developed as an independent project. It is not a
      subsidiary, collection, or branded initiative of another organization.
      Future scholarly, archival, educational, or institutional collaborations
      may be acknowledged individually without changing that independent
      identity.
    </p>
  </article>
</BaseLayout>

<style>
  .about-page {
    padding-block: clamp(3rem, 8vw, 7rem);
  }

  .about-page h2 {
    margin-top: clamp(2.75rem, 6vw, 4.5rem);
  }
</style>
